\par \pard\plain \s46{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
[More general/framing introduction to the Darwin half]}
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
In }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Voyage}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
of}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
the}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
\uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9c\uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Beagle}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
\uc3 \u8221\'e2\'80\'9d\uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
,}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 observation and classification merge: Darwin\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s record of having seen a creature is often rendered in terms already mediated by taxonomy and scientific precedence. When Darwin introduces the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9clizards\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d of the Galapagos, for example, he does not begin with description. Instead, he begins with the relational structure of a set of observations he has not yet reported: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cOf lizards there are four or five species; two probably belong to the South American genus Leiocephalus, and two to Amblyrhyncus. This remarkable genus was characterized by Mr Bell, from a stuffed specimen sent from Mexico\u8230\'e2\'80\'a6\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d(279). Though he begins with the vernacular \u8220\'e2\'80\'9clizards\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and continues to characterize his own observations, the sentence is not allowed to end until his observations have been contextualized within the annals of knowledge that already exists, or which has already been determined. Nor is this his final level of classification. Having placed his own observation within the body of inherited knowledge, he continues to classify that classification itself within the larger body of taxonomic knowledge, providing a citation to Bell. This structure is unsurprising, a feature of diligent scientific writing\u8212\'e2\'80\'94the young Darwin, having never published, wants to make sure his writing meets the standards of the discipline. What is more surprising, however, is that the same recourse to classification characterizes his notes: his written observations are being mediated by his predecessors at the earliest stages. The first mention of one such lizard in the Galapagos notes proper (excluding \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cAmblyrhyncus\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d in the front flap, which appears to be a post-hoc description of contents) is \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cViviparous Lizard near Leposoma of Spix\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (\uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Notebooks}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 430, 8A). Again, Darwin begins with observation and vernacular naming, only to quickly mediate it with taxonomic placement and citation[^2]. This description may be a characterization of scientific process and by no means unique to Darwin, but Darwin imports the structure of classification into a more general account, even into the syntax of his loosely scientific narrative. In so doing, he reveals the extent to which classification is barely posterior to observation\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94and may even be anterior to it.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
In a sense, this very anteriority of knowledge, this commitment to contribute to what has already been established, defined the expedition itself. Robert FitzRoy, the expedition\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s captain, was careful to outfit the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cBeagle\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d with the tools necessary for observation, including chronometers, surveying devices, and other expensive instrumentation. This equipage was meant merely to allow for observation, but the choice of instruments was also already determining the character of observation to a considerable extent\u8212\'e2\'80\'94as Janet Browne and Michael Neve point out, the chronometers, \u8220\'e2\'80\'9c\uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
when}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
calibrated}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
against}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
those}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
held}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
at}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Greenwich}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, would enable him to determine the ship\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s longitude far more accurately than had previously been attempted\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (4, emphasis mine). Without a contextualizing system such as the reference to Greenwich time, instrumentation is useless. Accuracy is a factor not only of the fine gradations of measurement, but the relation of those measurements to every measurement preceding it. The conditions for preparation are already determining the type of observation that will be able to be made. As a kind of human instrumentation, Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s own calibration comes in the form of his education. When he cites \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cMr Bell\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d immediately after logging an observation, he is placing what he has seen in the context of his own experience as a student as well as in the context of the naturalists before him. Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s willingness to contextualize and temper what he has seen with what others before him have seen even determined his selection for the trip: when FitzRoy writes to the Admiralty of the British Navy in 1831 asking for a fitting scientific companion, Darwin is recommended because of his success in the professional and social structures of Cambridge (Browne and Neve 5). He is chosen for his ability in precisely this type of replication of knowledge.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Darwin\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s thinking about collection, taxonomy, and the relationship of the individual to the species also has a corollary in the way that he makes comparisons: as he uses it, comparison is a prelude to classification, but it is also restricted by the existing taxonomic hierarchy. In their study on the role of behavioral observations in the development of evolutionary theory, Arist\uc2 \u243\'c3\'b3bulo P\u233\'c3\'a9rez, Germ\u225\'c3\'a1n Guti\u233\'c3\'a9rrez, and Alejandro Segura classify Darwin\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s observations within their own taxonomic system, pointing out that 11% of Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s observations are rendered as comparisons. They specify the type of comparisons that occur: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cel uso de la comparaci\uc2 \u243\'c3\'b3n tanto de las estructuras anat\u243\'c3\'b3micas como de sus funciones, le permite a Darwin dar cuenta de los procesos evolutivos en las especies\uc3 \u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (P\uc2 \u233\'c3\'a9rez et al. 514).[^4.1] That these comparisons occur on the anatomical and functional level reveals their purpose. By perceptually and textually dissecting the creatures of the Galapagos, Darwin is able to draw lines of association among entries in a taxonomy based on physical and behavioral similarity, lines that situate an entry with relation to those contiguous to it.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
To make such piecemeal comparisons, though, requires a certain kind of observation; the process of dissection, as with classification, begins on the level of perception. Description, which characterizes 51% of Darwin\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s observations (Per\uc2 \u233\'c3\'a9z et al. 513), is often just a prelude to the taxonomizing comparison. To return to the Amblyrhyncus genus: \uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cIn size perhaps they are a little inferior to the latter, but several of them weighed between 10 and 15 pounds each. The colour of their belly, front legs, and head (excepting the crown which is nearly white), is a dirty yellowish-orange: the back is a brownish-red, which in the younger specimens is darker\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (282). Two dissections occur: of the animal, which is separated into parts and parts of parts; and of the observations, which are separated into type by what is being recorded (size, weight, color). The two dissections allow for comparison, but descriptively they break the Amblyrhyncus into pieces. The organic creature becomes a collection of disparate observations, separated, classified, and set aside for later analysis; but the perceptual act, the subjective apprehension of a living being, is likewise divided in the name of objective description.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The word \uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9ccollection\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d is used deliberately here, for Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s love of \uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
collecting}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 as a means of and predecessor to understanding is well documented; moreover, the logic of the collection is useful as a description of the }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Voyage}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 project and its epistemological situation. As a child, Darwin had a marked and unusually diligent love of collecting natural specimens, which continued well into the time of his \uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cBeagle\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d voyage (Rosenberg 85). His role as a collector as well as a natural historian proceeded to such a degree that Robert McCormick, the expedition\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s senior naturalist in charge of the expedition\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s official collection, left the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cBeagle\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d at its first port, outraged by the presence of a competing collector (Browne and Neve 11). That Darwin was collecting as well as cataloguing is significant insofar as it provides a lens through which to see his sense of his own project: a collection is a reorganization, and representation in miniature, of the ecological environment from which it is pulled.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Considering the }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Voyage}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 as a linked set of collections in itself also explains certain acts of organization\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94and reorganization\u8212\'e2\'80\'94that occur in the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cGalapagos Archipelago\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d chapter. Both structurally and in specific instances, Darwin shows his hand in organizing his observations according to a logic internal to his project; this logic is reconcilable with the antecedent body of natural history that informs his observations, but it is not entirely identifiable with it. In presenting the beaks of finches, for example, his own organization as a collector comes into conflict with a more scientific and taxonomic organization. At first, he points out that \u8220\'e2\'80\'9ca nearly perfect gradation may be traced, from a beak extraordinarily thick, to one so fine, that it may be compared to that of a warbler\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (287). Soon after, however, his own organization of specimens as a collector gives way to a structure more consistent with taxonomic hierarchy: >I very much suspect, that certain members of the series are confined to different islands; therefore, if the collection had been made on any \uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
one}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 island, it would not have presented so perfect a gradation. It is clear, that if several islands have each their peculiar species of the same genera, when these are placed together, they will have a wide range of character. But there is not space in this work, to enter on this curious subject. (288)}
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
This is one of the most important passages of the \uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cGalapagos Archipelago\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d chapter of the \uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Voyage}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 from a scientific perspective, as it raises the questions of transmutation of species that would later form the foundation for his theory of evolution, but the passage also exhibits a conflict between two different kinds of organization. The first, hypothetical one is structured according to the set of possible relationships to be drawn among the specimens. But this structure, and the organizing act that precedes it, is rejected in favor}
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Tension between the genres of travelogue, diary, and work of natural history leads to a conflicted and amorphous structure of the chapter. The early part of the chapter is marked by dated entries, which gives the sense if not of a narrative than at least of a chronology. Passages of scientific description and anecdote mingle, placing emphasis on Darwin as an observer situated in time and place. In what is ostensibly still the October 3rd entry, though, this chronological frame gives way to the purely taxonomic, describing time and place but somehow hovering above and outside of it. Where paragraphs in the section had previously begun with phrases like \uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cDuring another day\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cDuring the greater part of our week,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d an pronouncement that Darwin \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cwill now offer a few general observations on the natural history of these islands\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d initiates a new structure according taxonomic categories (from family to order down to species)(273-4). Paragraphs now begin: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cOf mammalia\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (275); \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cI will first describe the habits of the tortoise\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (276); \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cTo conclude with the order of reptiles\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (285). By merging structures, Darwin also merges types of record; the personal, the anecdotal, the experimental, and the taxonomic become different entries in a textual, archipelagic collection. Darwin himself becomes a part of the collection.[^4.2] **[What about the beaks? The gradient thing is important]\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
This treatment of the individual organism with relation to its species becomes clearer when considered in the context of the antecedent theories of Jean Baptiste Lamarck and Georges Cuvier,[^5] the hegemonic theories explaining the transmutation of species prior to Darwin, which Darwin reacts against in the observations of his }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Voyage}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
. There is no evidence to suggest that Darwin fully accepted Lamarck\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s or Cuvier\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s theories\u8212\'e2\'80\'94in fact, it is more probable that he generally rejected them in adherence to Charles Lyell refutation in his \uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Principles}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
of}{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Geology}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, a book that influenced Darwin greatly (Chancellor and Van Wyhe 38). Nevertheless, Darwin\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s rare gestures toward explanation or theorization implicitly endorse a relationship between hereditary traits and environment, which defines Lamarck\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s and Cuvier\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s contributions. Unlike Lamarck\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s and Cuvier\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s theories, however, the relationship Darwin posits of a species to its environment does not affect physical inheritance; instead, Darwin is focused almost entirely on behavioral adaptation and species learning. Concluding a passage in which he experimentally teases a lizard, driving it to a shore\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s edge to prove its fear of water and finally throwing it into a pond, Darwin says the hydrophobia under pressure is \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cprobably urged by a fixed and hereditary instinct that the shore is its place of safety,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d since \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cthis reptile has no enemy whatever on shore\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (281). At issue in this explanation is the question of how behavioral characteristics emerge. This is a major preoccupation of Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s stay on the archipelago, prompting him to pull tails, knock on shells, and commit other acts of minor experimental violence. In pondering the lizard, Darwin is unwilling to suggest an explanation of the individual behavior. Instead, he turns immediately to an explanation on the level of species. He concludes the Galapagos chapter with another such explanation, this time rendered as the beginning of a more general theory: >From the foregoing statements we may, I think, conclude that the >wildness of birds with regard to man\u8230\'e2\'80\'a6is not acquired by them in a >short time, even when much persecuted; but that in the course of >successive generations it becomes hereditary. With domesticated animals >we are accustomed to see instincts becoming hereditary; but with those >in a state of nature, it is more rare to discover instances of such an >acquired knowledge.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The emphasis on the time necessary for such changes to occur may point to Darwin\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s debt to Lyell,[^6] but any other assertions of influence here are more difficult to sustain. Though he seems to have learned to focus on environmental factors from Lamarck and Cuvier, his focus on behavior departs from their theories. Moreover, the way he discusses environment with relation to inheritance leads to a tension between knowledge acquired by the individual and inherited from antecedents. The difference between \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cdomesticated\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d animals and those \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cin a state of nature\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d would appear to be learned behaviors in response to environment. Syntactically, though, Darwin equates \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cinstincts becoming hereditary\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cacquired knowledge\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d on the level of the species. The implicit argument, then, seems to be that an individual of a species learns a certain behavioral trait and passes it on to its progeny by an act of teaching; this act repeated over an enormous length of time \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cbecomes hereditary.\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d Without a physical corollary to the act of acquiring knowledge\u8212\'e2\'80\'94and if he rejects Lamarck and Cuvier, no physical corollary yet exists\u8212\'e2\'80\'94no other explanation of species-level learning makes sense. In not-quite-theorizing the way that behaviors become biologically inscribed on successive generations, Darwin identifies the theoretical gap that he will eventually come to fill.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
In lieu of a theory of physical transmutation, Darwin focuses on the development of communal knowledge on the level of the species\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94which he understands biologically as instinct. His experiments test the limits of two bodies of knowledge: scientific knowledge (the act of classification) and animal knowledge (the act of survival). Observation comes to establish, then, not only the place of the species in the natural historian\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s taxonomy, but also the state of the collective knowledge of the non-human species; the knowledge structures of the collector and the collection overlap. Teaching and learning as processes of communal development define both Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s sense of himself as a young scientist and his first gestures toward an evolutionary theory. In both cases, the individual is defined in relation to the larger group\u8212\'e2\'80\'94whether as a contributor to a communal body of knowledge or as an entry in a vast taxonomy. The \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cGalapagos Archipelago\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d chapter of \uc1 }{\i\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch
