Melville}
\par \pard\plain \s46{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
If Darwin compulsively renders his developing self with respect to the body of scientific knowledge that precedes him\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94whether by deferring his classification, by allowing his perception to be mediated by the perceptions of his predecessors, or by relentlessly understanding himself as a student, only registering explanation and theorization in the most tentative terms\u8212\'e2\'80\'94then Herman Melville, writing on the same islands in a very similar moment, can only be said to radically abnegate all such bodies of knowledge. Where Darwin places himself within a framework, Melville destroys the framework. What Darwin takes as a foundation, Melville takes as an at best epistemologically suspicious set of totalizing statements. And what Darwin takes as a social frame\u8212\'e2\'80\'94the academy, career, and even identity as human\u8212\'e2\'80\'94Melville understands as the residue domination, an attempt to shackle the self with having already understood. Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s account of the Galapagos begins with a radical display of not-knowing, which has been well documented,[^6] but it quickly moves into the conditions necessary for knowledge and the phenomenal experience of encountering anterior bodies of knowledge\u8212\'e2\'80\'94a world in which classification conquers, in which every encountered thing is subject to the inhibition of understanding by another epistemological agent, subject to constitution by another discourse. Finally, he presents naming and the assertion of knowledge as acts of conquering that prevent the existence of other, fully constituted selves, linking epistemological mastery with personal domination.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
In \uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cThe Alternative Taxonomies of Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s \u8216\'e2\'80\'98The Encantadas,\u8217\'e2\'80\'99\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d Denise Tanyol also compares Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s and Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s opposed treatments of the Galapagos, arguing that Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s destabilization of taxonomy is a way of reclaiming for the islands their unknowability and thereby thwarting the basically imperial motivations of Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s survey. In the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cRock Rodondo\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d sketch, she argues, Melville resists taxonomic classification in two steps, first disputing valuation according to position in a hierarchy and then disrupting the act of classification by which such hierarchies are constructed (259-60). He continues to create \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cnew, imaginative approaches to the task of classification,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and in so doing \u8220\'e2\'80\'9creveal[s] the subjectivity\u8212\'e2\'80\'94and ultimately the self-interest\u8212\'e2\'80\'94underlying any ostensibly objective scientific system of classification\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (262-3). Drawing on Michel Imbert and Carolyn Karcher, she reads Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s rejection of taxonomic classification as a warning against the imperialism inherent in such projects, and concludes by situating Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s de- and reconstruction of the naturalist\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s taxonomy as a broadside aimed at empire itself (264-5, 278-9). Comparing the ways that such classifications and reclassifications affect the observer instead of the observed, though, reveals the extent to which observation and classification of something external is also always a construction of the self in Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cEncantadas.\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d The inherent subjectivity of classification, then, does more than undermine the classification. Subjective classification for Melville becomes an act of dual-rendering of the observer and the observed, each according to terms established by the other. Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s encounters with previously established systems of naming and hierarchy are thus encounters with the imprints of other minds\u8212\'e2\'80\'94imprints that, unless disputed, prevent new self-construction through unalloyed seeing and naming. Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s dissent runs deeper than in Tanyol\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s representation of it, is more ontological than political: by sweeping away the scientific rendering of the Galapagos, Melville asserts a right to individual experience unmediated by previous experiences of it. To encounter an environment already rendered, already understood and classified, is to encounter a self already pre-constructed and thus enslaved.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Two ways of seeing and classifying distinctly separate Melville\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s account of life on the Galapagos from Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s. The first is the way that Melville uses comparisons. As shown above, Darwin uses comparisons in order to put individual observations in the context of a larger taxonomic hierarchy. The act of observation that precedes classification is already influenced by the classifying act, and seeing for Darwin becomes an anatomical dissection structured to allow for that hierarchical placement. In stark contrast, Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s comparisons seem willfully to cross the least porous lines of the naturalist\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s taxonomy as well as less scientific systems of classification. Non-human is compared to human, animal to vegetable, inorganic to organic matter. Tortoises are subject to perhaps the most and widest-ranging comparisons, being as they are the focus of the early sketches. Though many other features and inhabitants of the Gallapagos are subject to similar comparison, each type of Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s cross-taxonomic comparisons can be found in passages on the tortoises. In one moment they are \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cgrim as blacksmiths,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d only to become mounts for Brahmin in the same paragraph (303). Their shells are considered independently of the rest of their bodies in an act of perceptual dissection that seems at first reminiscent of Darwin; where Darwin might proceed from this dissection to use the shell as a key for taxonomic placement, though, Melville drastically resituates the shell in a context of trans-species protection and ancientness, associating it with medieval human history by calling it \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cliving mail\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and \u8220\'e2\'80\'9ca citadel\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (301). The same processes that Darwin uses for placement, Melville uses for displacement. In a particularly audacious moment, he even invokes scientific discourse to describe his radical declassification: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9c[as I beheld] scars strangely widened, swollen, half obliterate, and yet distorted like those sometimes found in the bark of very hoary trees, I seemed an antiquary of a geologist, studying the bird-tracks and ciphers upon the exhumed slates trod by incredible creatures whose very ghosts are now defunct\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (301). Scars that at first exhibit the features of animal matter (becoming \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cswollen\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d) become a means of linking them to \u8220\'e2\'80\'9choary trees,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d until suddenly Melville is a \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cgeologist\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d looking for fossils. In one sweeping sentence, tortoises are transformed from animal to vegetable to mineral, becoming understandable not just in different taxonomic kingdoms, but also different branches of science. The boundlessness of the creatures becomes such that even the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cantiquary geologist\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d finds them \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cincredible\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and is only able to discuss them in such supernatural a context as their \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cghosts.\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s comparisons acknowledge the taxonomic hierarchies, but they only do so as a means of violating them with greater specificity.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The second way that Melville\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s representation of life forms differs from Darwin\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s is his emphasis on multiple possible (and valid) perspectives. Darwin uses the habitual present tense, as I argue above, to relate observations of individual organisms to its species as a whole; in doing so, he also privileges a single perspective (his) by implicitly making it representative of all possible observations of a specimen of the species. In Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s Rock Rodondo section (\u8220\'e2\'80\'9cSketch Third\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d) and elsewhere, though, individual observations from different perspectives indicate different things even about a single specimen, and none of them is clearly presented as correct\u8212\'e2\'80\'94the rock only appears to be a rock when one is standing on it, but elsewhere it appears to be \u8220\'e2\'80\'9csome Spanish Admiral\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s ship\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d or is reminiscent of a \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cBell Tower of St.\~ Mark\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (305).[^7] Taking Rock Rodondo as in part a physicalization of taxonomy itself\u8212\'e2\'80\'94it is stratified, supporting, containing, and framing different gradations of species, even if subversively as Tanyol suggests\u8212\'e2\'80\'94Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s comment about the ephemerality of form is applied directly to systems of classification. Even when describing the mutable hierarchy of species from his narrator\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s position on the rock, Melville is careful to emphasize the perspectival contingency of his observations. Moments of classificatory pronouncement are interrupted by passages of chaos and motion in which the observer is emphasized. As the avian portion of the Rock Rodondo taxonomy departs the classifying structure, entering the undifferentiated mass above, the narrator is situated with a grammatical subject \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cI\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d. Verbs of perception which are somewhat rare up to this point appear in a cluster\u8212\'e2\'80\'94\u8220\'e2\'80\'9chear,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cgaze,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cbehold\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d appear in two contiguous sentences\u8212\'e2\'80\'94which marks a synesthetic blending of observations: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cclear, silver, bugle-like notes unbrokenly [fall], like oblique lines of swift-slanting rain in a cascading shower\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (311). Even categories of perception are mutable depending on the perspective assumed.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
What is true of literal, physical perspective with respect to Rock Rodondo is also true of epistemological perspective and the beliefs of the observer. The belief of some mariners in magical enchantment is faithfully related as a predecessor to other (albeit corrupted) forms of discourse\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94and, perhaps because it does not seem as necessary, enchantment is the explanation faced with the least representational subversion. Unlike Darwin, who contradicts the Galapagos residents\u8217\'e2\'80\'99 complaints of poverty with his own observations about their conditions,[^8] Melville privileges all statements of knowledge by endorsing none and presenting each as flawed and contingent. The explanation for this catholic approval of perspectives is presented in a submerged theory of what constitutes knowledge, and more particularly how knowledge is constituted, which begins \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cSketch Fourth\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d: > If you seek to ascend Rock Rodondo, take the following prescription. Go three voyages round the world as a main-royal-man of the tallest frigate that floats; then serve a year or two apprenticeship to the guides who conduct strangers up the Peak of Teneriffe; and as many more respectively to a rope-dancer, an Indian juggler, and a chamois. This done, come and be rewarded by the view from our tower. How we get there, we alone know. If we sought to tell others, what the wiser were they? Suffice it, that here at the summit you and I stand.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Melville\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s narrator Tarnmoor provides a \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cprescription\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d specific enough that it can be taken to be his personal history. To \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cascend Rock Rodondo,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d then\u8212\'e2\'80\'94that is, to see exactly what Melville has seen and reported, as it has already been shown to be a mutable construct\u8212\'e2\'80\'94is only possible if you have done everything that Tarnmoor has done and, presumably, become Tarnmoor thereby. By denying \u8220\'e2\'80\'9ctell[ing]\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d as a means of attaining wisdom, Tarnmoor implicitly excludes teaching as a means of learning. What is seen is a product of the observer, the observer is formed by what that observer knows, and what is known is a product exclusively of experience. Seeing, being, and knowing all become bound in Tarnmoor\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s definition of self. In Melville\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s rendering of classification, the way of seeing becomes a unique and untransferable thing, rendering any deference to anterior bodies of knowledge impossible without a fundamental transformation of the self.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Such transformation\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94of the self, but also of the thing seen\u8212\'e2\'80\'94define the ways of seeing that Tarnmoor posits and enacts. Seeing and being seen lead to dual transmutation and simultaneous constitution of subject and object: not only does what is seen seem literally to change under the gaze of the observer, but the observer too is redefined by the act of seeing, through the process of experience that Tarnmoor identifies as the link between seeing, knowing, and being. A relationship of mirroring and imprinting is established early in \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cSketch First\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d: >\u8220\'e2\'80\'9cAnd as for solitariness; the great forests of the north, the expanses of unnavigated waters, the Greenland ice-fields, are the profoundest of solitudes to a human observer; still the magic of their changeable tides and seasons mitigates their terror; because, though unvisited by men, those forests are visited by May; the remotest seas reflect familiar stars even as Lake Erie does; and in the clear air of a fine Polar day, the irradiated, azure ice shows beautifully as malachite\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (288-9).\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Attributes more accurately ascribed to the human observer become ascribed to features of the landscape. The \uc3 \u8220\'e2\'80\'9csolitariness\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d referred to by way of introduction is not rendered as a product of the observer\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s distance from other people. Rather, it becomes associated with the thing seen, even to the point of redefining them as themselves \u8220\'e2\'80\'9csolitudes\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d\u8212\'e2\'80\'94what is perceived as an attribute becomes the substance itself. An immediate parallel is offered in the act of reflection. Just as the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cunnavigated waters\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cthe Greenland ice-fields\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d are redefined by the solitariness of the observer, so is the unfamiliar reflective surface redefined by what it reflects, \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cMay.\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d But what finally redefines them is not May itself, but the familiarity of May and its ability to transform the barren landscapes it touches. This receptive landscape forms at once a parallel and counterpoint to the islands, modeling the act of reflection while demonstrating the familiarity and comfort the islands lack. The islands, by contrast, seem \u8220\'e2\'80\'9c[a]pples of Sodom, after touching\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d\u8212\'e2\'80\'94ruined by the mere act of interaction, destroyed by apprehension.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The reflection analogy would seem to imply that the object reverts to its natural state as soon as it is released from the gaze of the observer\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94but this does not seem to be the case in Tarnmoor\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s rendering of perceptual transformation. Like the apple of Sodom, once transformed, the perceived object stays transformed. The frequent recourse to enchantment as an explanation here becomes definitional: the implied enchanter exercises its will upon a creature or thing and changes its identity forever. Elsewhere, the mere act of association is shown to be enough for permanently transformation, and not only in the eyes of the original observer. Tarnmoor says of human ruins: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9clike all else which has but once been associated with humanity, they still awaken in us some thoughts of sympathy, however sad\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (288). This sympathetic association with humanity is not limited to those things whose origin is human, either. Later, it is applied to the tortoises. The moment of Tarnmoor\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s greatest sympathy with the tortoises culminates with their being \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cassociated with humanity\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cSuch worshipful venerableness of aspect! \u8230\'e2\'80\'a6I no more saw three tortoises. They expanded\u8212\'e2\'80\'94became transfigured. I seemed to see three Roman Coliseums in magnificent decay\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (300). Association gives way to transformation; the attribute becomes the substance. Elsewhere tortoises are literally inscribed with associations: Tarnmoore describes \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cthe ghost of a gigantic tortoise, with \u8217\'e2\'80\'99Memento *****\u8217\'e2\'80\'99 burning in live letters upon his back" (296). The inscription becomes a material thing without quite giving up its liveness as an extension of a human. Perceptions are not content to remain in the mind of the observer. Enchantment becomes an operative mode in every perceptive act in \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cThe Encantadas.\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d Encounters with things previously unseen lead to simultaneous transformation, but encounters with those things encountered before are encounters with the effects of previous observers\u8212\'e2\'80\'94whether in the form of things \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cbut once associated with humanity\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d or islands named after explorers. The \u8220\'e2\'80\'9csolitude\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d of the frozen plains in the reflection analogy above, then, is not just a product of the distance of those plains from civilization. It arises from the waters being \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cunnavigated,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d having never been encountered, never imprinted with the traces of another mind. Via negativa, Melville invokes the presence of predecessors in an encounter with everything previously seen: all things are marked, stamped, or otherwise transformed with the vestiges of another mind.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Marked, stamped, imprinted\uc3 \u8212\'e2\'80\'94if the acts of perceiving, naming, or understanding are acts of dual creation of self and other, a certain amount of authorship is implicit. In claiming that such natural and inevitable acts as perception and thought are authorial, Tarnmoor situates authorship as a fundamental part of personal experience, and asserts perceptual ownership and concomitant self-authorship as natural rights. In \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cSketch Eighth,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d Hunilla, the widow so problematically described as a \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cCholo\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d and \u8220\'e2\'80\'9chalf-breed,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d is presented as the author of the experiences by which she is defined as \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cthe heroine of her tale\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d\u8212\'e2\'80\'94and in her reverential narrative treatment, almost the heroine of \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cThe Encantadas.\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d In the narration of the event that defines her, Hunilla\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s perspectival situation is repetitively emphasized, as is the rendering of image and memory. When her husband and brother sink, the narrative proper is concluded with \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cboth adventurers perished before Hunilla\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s eyes,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d only to be chiasmatically repeated in the beginning of the next paragraph: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cBefore Hunilla\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s eyes they sank\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (353). Through the rest of the paragraph terms of perception dominate, echoing the earlier passage in \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cRock Rodondo\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d but with an unmistakable emphasis of a single perspective. This perspective is both bounded and aestheticized by Hunilla\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s own actions as she watches, entranced: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cHunilla had withdrawn the branches to one side, and held them so. They formed an oval frame, through which the bluely boundless sea rolled like a painted one. And there, the invisible painter painted to her view the wave-tossed and disjointed raft, its once level logs slantingly upheaved, as raking masts, and the four struggling arms undistinguishable among them\u8230\'e2\'80\'a6. Death in a silent picture; a dream of the eye; such vanishing shapes as the mirage shows\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (353-4). The image is again indeterminate, defined by misperception of \u8220\'e2\'80\'9craking masts\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d in a further echo of the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cRock Rodondo\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d section. But this time misperception is a feature of authorship. Though the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cinvisible painter paint[s]\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d the scene, and not Hunilla, Hunilla is the one who creates the frame that allows the invisible painting to occur. Perception is an act devoid of agency, but it is nevertheless an act of creation. What was previously presented as multiple perspectives contingent on misperception\u8212\'e2\'80\'94the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cdream of the eye,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d the product of \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cmirage\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d\u8212\'e2\'80\'94are now indicative of personal creation. Later, she bounds her experience in her own terms, marking time in a way that defies all previous systems (Tanyol ###). In Hunilla\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s case, these moments of rendering are the only definition she is allowed. Her race is from the beginning both defining and hopelessly ambiguous: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9ccholo\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d establishes an indeterminacy that allows her to become associated with the dogs she keeps via \u8220\'e2\'80\'9chalf-breed.\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d The entire identity Melville affords her arises from this one experience, the rendering of which she herself is the author. In a very real and very narrative sense, then, she is the author of herself, and this self-authorship begins with perceptual rendering.\uc1 }
\par \pard\plain \s29\sb86\sa86{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Consistent with the implicit connection of self-construction and perception, Melville\uc3 \u8217\'e2\'80\'99s representation of slavery begins with an act of competing classifications, linking such classification of others with domination of them. Oberlus\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s subjugation of other creatures is represented as a struggle to establish dominance of classification and representation. \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cThe long habit of sole dominion over every object round him\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d engenders in Oberlus \u8220\'e2\'80\'9ca vast idea of his own importance, together with a pure animal sort of scorn for all the rest of the universe\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (378): in Oberlus\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s world, everything he sees is a part of his dominion, which he takes as an organizing taxonomy of his own\u8212\'e2\'80\'94everything that exists is subjugated to him. His is a simple hierarchy, yet hierarchy it is. Nevertheless, Oberlus\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s personal taxonomy requires proving; but in order to prove it, he needs to prove his conception of himself, \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cto prove his potency upon the first specimen of humanity which should fall unbefriended into his hands\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (379). In this case, the classification of all other creatures begins with a conception of self, not only of self as master but of self as somehow taxonomically other than all else\u8212\'e2\'80\'94Oberlus distinguishes himself from the \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cspecimen[s] of humanity\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d which he hopes to conquer. When he finally has his chance to prove his hierarchical view of the universe, it occurs through dialectical means. Though his domination is enforced by physical means (a \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cblunderbuss,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d or a kind of musket), it is initiated and refuted through competitive classification. [Can I get Hegel in here??] When, after the abortive first attempt, he succeeds in enforcing his domination by treating his slaves \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cas creatures of an inferior race,\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d the power of definition resides with him. He is free to classify them as he will, and he \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cgaffles his four animals animals, and makes murderers of them; out of cowards fitly manufacturing bravos\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (384). This is only allowed to happen, however, because they submit to Oberlus\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s taxonomy: \u8220\'e2\'80\'9cfinding themselves entirely dependent upon Oberlus\u8230\'e2\'80\'a6they willingly enlist under him, becoming his humble slaves, and Oberlus the most incredible of tyrants\u8221\'e2\'80\'9d (383). In the Oberlus parable, domination begins with willful submission to a taxonomy\u8212\'e2\'80\'94whether biological or political, as it is both in the case of Oberlus\u8212\'e2\'80\'94in which one is inferior to another being. Personal domination begins with a willingness to submit to other explanations about the state of the physical world, as in forfeiting one\u8217\'e2\'80\'99s own right to determine perception as such, one foregoes the right to self-determination. To submit to another set of explanations is, in the end, just to submit.\uc1 }
